The stage-0 fuzzer exposed a chain: dispatch reorder -> setPendingCall
-EAGAIN reply (dar-gwn.6.2 guard) -> UDS reply-stream shift (the transport
matches replies to requests by ORDER, no correlation ids) -> guest sends
interrupt_exit out of step -> InterruptExit pops _interrupts out from under
a still-in-flight interrupt_enter fiber -> _interrupts.top() on an empty
stack is UB -> jumpToResume(context=0x2) SIGSEGV (captured 3/3 seeds with
-g backtraces at thread.cpp:2833).

Defensive layer, all sites loud in the log and only reachable under desync:
- interrupt_enter bails out gracefully on an empty interrupt stack (entry)
  and skips the interrupted-call resume / epilogue frame access if the frame
  vanished across its suspension points;
- interrupt_exit refuses to pop while the matching enter is still in flight
  (_interruptedForSignal) or when the stack is empty;
- _deactivateCallLocked / syscallReturn / pushCallReply / processSignal /
  handleSignal fall back to the plain active-call slot instead of top()-UB.

The reply-stream desync itself (order-based UDS matching + EAGAIN retries)
is a transport-protocol hole tracked for a later stage; this commit makes
the server SURVIVE it instead of corrupting interrupt state.
